At least 40 schoolgirls were impregnated daily in the first half of last year in Kakamega County, according to data from the County Government  Statistics released by the County Department of Reproductive Health and Services show that 8,000 cases of teen pregnancies were recorded between January and June, 2020.  County Coordinator in charge of Reproductive Health and Services Imelda Baraza said the number of teen pregnancies was worrying.  “We expected the numbers to go down this year since children are in school, unlike last year when learners were at home,” said Ms Baraza.  According to the report, 960 pregnancy cases were recorded in schoolgirls aged between 10 and 14, while there were 7,040 cases involving teenagers aged between 15 and 18 years. Records show that the county had 17,000 reported cases of teen pregnancies in 2018.  Ministry in plan to fund birth control from State coffers  Family planning uptake drops due to Covid-19  Lack of contraceptives linked to increased maternal deaths  Special Report: Teenage dads forced to quit school to raise their children Baraza was speaking at the Kakamega General and Referral Hospital during the launch of the Young Mothers' Club, which aims to teach pregnant teens and young mothers about family planning and antenatal care.   Teens forced to take birth control pills in Nakuru as teen pregnancy sky-rockets  Mabwawa kuchimbwa Budalangi ili kuzuia mafuriko | Mbiu ya KTN 12th May 2020  How to improve awareness on contraception | Black and White By John Shilitsa | 40 minutes ago By Robert Amalemba | 23 hours ago By Micah Sali | 4 days ago By Nathan Ochunge | 7 days ago